<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I read NPK numbers on fertilizer?", answer: "The three numbers on a fertilizer bag — 10-10-10, 21-0-0, 16-4-8 — are the percentages by weight of nitrogen (N), phosphorus as P2O5 (P), and potassium as K2O (K). A 50 lb bag of 21-0-0 contains 10.5 lb of actual nitrogen (50 × 0.21), zero phosphorus, and zero potassium. The rest is carrier and filler. Fertilizer is applied based on pounds of actual nitrogen per 1,000 square feet, not pounds of fertilizer product." },
  { question: "How much nitrogen should I apply to my lawn?", answer: "Cool season grasses like Kentucky bluegrass, tall fescue, and perennial ryegrass need about 2 to 4 pounds of actual nitrogen per 1,000 square feet per year, split into 3 or 4 applications in spring and fall. Warm season grasses like bermudagrass, zoysia, and St. Augustine need 3 to 6 pounds per year, applied from late spring through summer. Start at the low end if you bag clippings and the high end if you mulch back." },
  { question: "How do I calculate pounds of fertilizer from a rate?", answer: "Divide the desired pounds of nitrogen per 1,000 square feet by the decimal N percentage of your fertilizer. For 1 lb of N per 1,000 sq ft using 21-0-0, you need 1 / 0.21 = 4.76 lb of product per 1,000 sq ft. For a 5,000 sq ft lawn, multiply by 5: 23.8 lb of fertilizer. The calculator handles the conversion automatically once you enter area, rate, and N percent." },
  { question: "Can you over-fertilize a lawn?", answer: "Yes — over-fertilization causes thatch buildup, disease, and burned grass, and excess nitrogen runs off into waterways. Never apply more than 1 lb of actual nitrogen per 1,000 sq ft in a single application of quick-release fertilizer. Slow-release fertilizers can be applied at slightly higher rates because the nitrogen releases over 8 to 12 weeks rather than all at once." },
  { question: "Is organic fertilizer different?", answer: "Organic fertilizers like composted manure, blood meal, and feather meal have lower NPK numbers (blood meal is 12-0-0, feather meal is 12-0-0, alfalfa meal is 3-2-2), so you need to apply more product by weight to get the same amount of actual nitrogen. The calculator still works the same way — just use the organic fertilizer's first NPK number as the nitrogen percent." }
]) %>

